Author-Name: GIOVANNI CESPA 
Title: Information Sales and Insider Trading with Long-Lived Information 
Abstract:
 Fundamental information resembles in many respects a durable good. Hence,
 the effects of its incorporation into stock prices depend on who is the
 agent controlling its flow. Like a durable goods monopolist, a
 monopolistic analyst selling information intertemporally competes against
 herself. This forces her to partially relinquish control over the
 information flow to traders. Conversely, an insider solves the
 intertemporal competition problem through vertical integration, thus
 exerting tighter control over the information flow. Comparing market
 patterns I show that a dynamic market where information is provided by an
 analyst is "thicker" and "more informative" than one where an insider
 trades. Copyright 2008 by The American Finance Association. 
