Author-Name: DANIEL DORN 
Author-Name: GUR HUBERMAN 
Author-Name: PAUL SENGMUELLER 
Title: Correlated Trading and Returns 
Abstract:
 A German broker's clients place similar speculative trades and therefore
 tend to be on the same side of the market in a given stock during a given
 day, week, month, and quarter. Aggregate liquidity effects, short sale
 constraints, the systematic execution of limit orders (coordinated through
 price movements) or the correlated trading of other investors who pick off
 retail limit orders do not fully explain why retail investors trade
 similarly. Correlated market orders lead returns, presumably due to
 persistent speculative price pressure. Correlated limit orders also
 predict subsequent returns, consistent with executed limit orders being
 compensated for accommodating liquidity demands. Copyright 2008 by The American Finance Association. 
